043e22d9-23f6-41d2-a1f2-b68d2d077a9b.text: Data analytics is changing our world right now while you're watching this video. It is helping us make decisions, navigate through traffic, and even predict the best match-ups in your favorite team's lineup. Analytics are enabling us to address challenges that seemed impossible just a short time ago. Every day in the news, there are exciting stories about data-driven innovations in manufacturing, healthcare, space exploration, and many more. Data collected during the COVID-19 pandemic enabled governments and organizations across the globe to track outbreaks and mobilize resources. Taiwan, for example, used their National Health Insurance and Immigration Databases to create an outline of travel histories and symptoms of every person that left or entered the country. This type of creative analytical problem solving allowed health professionals to be better prepared to diagnose and identify the disease. In this course, you will learn the basic features and functions of data analytics, how data is collected and where it is stored, how data enables artificial intelligence and machine learning, and you will begin your journey to become a data professional. There are many opportunities to help drive forward these innovations as data analysts, scientists, and engineers. This is a rewarding career with the potential to really make a difference. Join us as we explore what is possible. (light music continues)

d959897c-a4d4-43e3-9afa-b951ff836041.text: Through your daily activities, you generate a great amount of data that can be volunteered, observed, or inferred. You volunteer data by filling out forms, posting photos and videos on social media, or consenting to website policies. Organizations also collect data about you through observations such as your location, stores you frequent, and websites you visit. Your personal style, likes and dislikes, and behavioral habits can even be inferred from your actions. By itself all this data can be rather meaningless; however, that changes immediately once you apply data analytics to your data. The process of taking data from its raw state and using it to inform useful actions is the realm of data analytics. Through the power of analytics, organizations can use your volunteered, observe, or inferred data to provide you with a personalized experience. (light music)

04c6bed2-a16c-4796-b9a8-8b58291625e6.text: The collection and analysis of data is making information readily available for many different purposes. We are more connected than ever. In our home, schools, work, and even the areas in which we play, advancements in technologies are generating large quantities of data. Everywhere you go and everything you do in this digital world becomes a new source of data. Data is being generated from sensors, devices, video, audio, networks, log files, transactional applications, the web, and social media. It is more commonly streaming over the networks and comes in a variety of sizes and formats. Among the uses for data in our daily lives are informing our decision-making. From the product recommendations that we see on our shopping sites to performance statistics on athletes to which groceries to stock in the market, our decisions are influenced by the results of data science and AI. Identifying the improvements to processes and products. Through the ability to use data collected from product reviews and ratings, manufacturers can modify designs or change their processes to produce and deliver better products to their consumers. Tracking and predicting events. One of the greatest benefits we can realize from analytics is the ability to track, isolate, and even predict events. A network engineer can use a dashboard to isolate areas of slowdown and immediately react to ensure it doesn't cause problems for users. Climate analysts can accurately predict the impacts of weather on all aspects of our economies. Self-driving cars can recognize hazards and take actions to avoid accidents. Enabling greater visibility into behaviors. Organizations now have greater visibility into how their products are used, the buying patterns of their customers, and the up-to-date logistical information to manage their lead times. This additional level of visibility enables managers to ensure that the right products are available for their customers in the shortest time possible. (uplifting music)

ea6fdab2-cc2f-4946-9f4c-e3bf2234f91e.text: Data analysis begins with understanding the types of data you're working with. Data can first be defined as quantitative or qualitative. Qualitative data is descriptive. It is typically represented as text, is non-numerical in nature, and is collected through surveys, questionnaires, interviews, or observations. An example of qualitative data is the reviews that are collected about various products on a shopping site. Quantitative data is numerical in nature. You are trying to quantify information. (upbeat music) Quantitative data can further be broken down into discrete and continuous data. Discrete data can only take on certain values, typically whole numbers. Examples of discrete data include account of transactions processed in a day or the number of people who visit a website each week. Continuous data is measured and can be represented in an infinite number of ways. An example of continuous data could be the average distance traveled by a moving car, which is constantly being updated as the car moves forward. Understanding quantitative versus qualitative data is an initial step, but strong familiarity with all types of data is necessary if you're going to be a versatile analyst. (upbeat music)

fb53fc84-f372-4b77-be73-2915e44e890c.text: Data science enables businesses to better understand the impact of their products and services, adjust their methods and goals and provide the customers with better products faster. The insights gain from data analysis can make a difference to the success of the business, as well as to the lives of their employees. There are multiple types of analysis that provide businesses with information that can drive innovation, improve efficiency and mitigate risk. The type of analytics to implement will depend on the problem that needs to be solved or questions that need to be answered. Trend analysis is one way to gain insights into key performance indicators, KPI, over time. One of our clients at Data Crunchers is a bicycle store that is having difficulty with attracting new customers. We can use analysis of the types of bicycles or services that their previous new customers purchased and during what time of the year they made their purchases. This analysis identifies trends in these purchases, such as many new customers are buying certain types of bikes at a specific time of the year. The store uses this information to purchase advertising during those time periods to target new buyers. Afterwards, store management can analyze sales data to determine the effectiveness of the advertising. Analytics can also be used to predict customer behaviors, gauge user satisfaction and even to identify patterns that can be used to train machines to perform complex functions.

1174c62f-be3a-4e90-b066-5a13c270b830.text: Businesses aren't the only ones that benefit from analytics. There are many examples of how humanitarian organizations are using the power of data to better serve their communities and the world. (upbeat music) Humanitarian aid organizations use insights gained from data analysis to predict the impacts of droughts and other weather events. The information obtained enables them to muster the appropriate resources to minimize the impact of vulnerable populations. The data from satellites, sensors, cameras, and even social media posts inform organizations about the numbers and locations of displaced persons that may need aid. Data collected during the recent pandemic informs researchers and medical personnel of how a virus might spread and mutate, ensuring that they can be better prepared in the future. IoT sensors and everyday things such as water pumps enable social entrepreneurs to determine how the individual pumps are operating and predict failures before they impact water supplies.

03f57430-116c-4418-951f-f55479e5fa1a.text: Here at Data Crunchers, data engineers ensure accessibility and availability of data for data scientists and data analysts. Data engineers integrate data from different sources and even perform some data cleaning. More data is being generated and stored than ever before. It's estimated that 2.5 quintillion bytes of data are generated each day. All this generated data must be securely stored and then processed for analysis. In this module, we will discuss the types of data being collected and where it's being stored. In some environments, there's likely to be some overlap between the roles of data analysts, data scientists, and even data engineers. There is no denying that this is a very exciting time to be a data engineer. (bright music)

4b404503-daea-4944-885a-bd3fd79191b8.text: The rise of big data means that more data is being generated and stored than ever before. The explosion of big data is responsible for 80% to 90% of all generated data, according to the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. All this generated data must be stored and then processed for analysis. This requires infrastructure specifically designed to securely store, manage and retrieve virtually limitless volumes of data, which could be a challenge for traditional on premises legacy data warehousing solutions. A data warehousing solution, stores data and files or folders in an organized manner that is readily available for reporting and data analysis. Traditional data warehousing solutions are best suited for structured data. They are not optimized to handle the large volumes of complex high velocity, unstructured big data and are challenged by the three v's of big data, volume, variety, and velocity. Big data requires distributed scalable non relational storage systems that can process large quantities of complex data in real time. Cloud service providers such as Amazon, Microsoft and Google each have popular cloud data warehousing products that can meet requirements and provide business solutions to warehouse and analyze their data. Cloud Data Warehousing provides distributed scalable non relational storage systems that can process large quantities of complex data, in real time. With cloud-based data warehousing, companies are not constrained by physical data centers and can dynamically scale storage resources to meet changing business budgets and requirements. In addition, the cloud offers the advantages of flexibility, collaboration and availability from anywhere. Moving from a traditional warehousing solution to a cloud based solution, allows companies to dynamically scale up or down data warehouse capacity, without upfront capital investments or time consuming infrastructure deployment. (upbeat music)

da743959-2e64-483d-9744-77e126ccc7d4.text: AI and machine learning are helping businesses make faster, better decisions, from helping us find potential cures for cancer, to better securing our financial transactions, to making autonomous vehicles safer and more. Why is this happening now at scale? Because processing and storage are rapidly becoming faster and cheaper, algorithms are smarter, and the AI ecosystem is larger. Let's take a closer look at an autonomous driving example to see the impact. There are several key stages in an AI and machine learning project. First, data is collected and prepared by data scientists. Then, training is performed to teach the required skills. And finally, inference is performed to make decisions based on new data. The value of AI is enormous, but there are challenges. For example, data preparation is very time-consuming, requiring up to 80% of data scientists' efforts. And data is often located across many sources. Data volumes are huge and growing fast, and that data is often sensitive or regulated, requiring workloads to be deployed on premises. Data volume and velocity create challenges across all stages, requiring high-performance systems that are adaptable to power these workloads at scale.

117975a2-cede-43af-b651-01effa700e01.text: At Data Crunchers, there are a few projects that are garnering a lot of attention from both our employees and clients. These projects are among our first that involve artificial intelligence, robots, and machine learning, the stuff that used to be only in science-fiction movies. One project that we're working on involves gathering data from images and GPS information. This will be used to train a robot to use AI-enabled recognition, to differentiate between weeds and crops, to reduce the use of chemical herbicides. That may not sound like a big project, but it requires a significant amount of unstructured data in the form of images and video that must be analyzed throughout the machine learning process. (upbeat music)

3440b074-4827-4120-bd17-73d37bb777d7.text: There are many exciting, time-saving uses for artificial intelligence technologies. Copy.AI is an AI-powered platform that helps you create blog entries, add copy, course pages, and more. You can even use it to write your next blog entry in just minutes. To use the Text Creation tool, enter the purpose, a few key words or phrases, and the text style that is appropriate for your purpose. As you can see, there are many different styles available. The Text Creation tool has access to a library of pre-written, natural language content and tools that you can customize. Once I click Create Copy, the tool presents several options for what kind of content it thinks would work best based on your information. You can choose which one appeals most to you based on the tone, length, and style, then customize it further if it doesn't meet all of your needs. The script for this video was prepared using the Text Creation tool. (gentle music)

44696dc4-eecf-46f2-99d4-cb38fdcbc1f4.text: It's all the rage these days, companies touting machine learning this or machine learning that, vendors promising a cure-all for every IT challenge. The hype is getting pretty thick. So, what exactly is machine learning? Traditionally, computers solve problems through programs or instructions given to them by a human. Machine learning just means the computer can figure out a solution without being specifically programmed. These machines have the ability to continuously learn by looking at data and finding patterns, and they do this much faster than a human could. Let's look at two key terms in machine learning: classifiers and algorithms. Classifiers are the workhorse of machine learning that categorize observations, while algorithms are the techniques that organize and orient classifiers. Often, machine learning requires training with sets of correct question and answer pairs that lets both the classifier and the algorithms do great work. Let's look at an example to see how it works. Classifiers analyze specific data patterns, not actual noses or eyes. And with enough training, they can pick your photo out of millions of options. So, how do we use machine learning in security? Envision an analytics pipeline that uses many hundreds of machine learning classifiers and algorithms all working together, analyzing millions of internal and external data points and events. The pipeline identifies and separates suspected malicious activity from the normal. It's then organized into specific events and then combined with actionable context for security teams. And it does all this at machine speed. Pretty amazing, right?

fbce7887-3eae-4cc8-aac4-a5c661a4a63a.text: It's been great to have you here working with us at Data Crunchers these last few days. I'd like a chance to review with you what you've experienced and talk to you a little bit about your future plans. We want to make sure that your internship propels you forward towards your career goals. You've had a chance to see how data and analytics are changing almost every facet of our lives. There are many opportunities for you to jump in and get started. Let's discuss some of the job roles and how you can prepare to take them on. (soft music)

1343f052-f158-4a17-95e0-01f24db2dbd9.text: One of the most common ways to showcase your analytic skills is to create and share a project portfolio. Portfolios are collections of examples of your work. The work that you showcase in a portfolio can be projects that you have done during your education, projects that you undertake using topics and data that you're interested in researching, or ones that are related to your current employment. The purpose of the portfolio is to expand upon the information that you provide in your resume, CV, or cover letter. The portfolio gives future employers insights into your interests and abilities. In addition to demonstrating your skills, employers are often interested in other information about you. Adding a blog to your portfolio gives you an opportunity to share how you became interested in pursuing a career as a data professional, topics, and projects that you want to pursue, and any competitions that you enter or win. (lively music)

1.4.2 Reflection
The world population continues to climb. The need to feed that growing population makes the agricultural sector more dependent on data than ever before. Agricultural farmers utilize data to determine the right weather, soil yield, supply and demand for the type of crops. These analytics impact what to plant, when to plant, when to harvest, and when to sell. For livestock farmers, data analytics drives breeding rates, land management, purchasing of hay and grain, and determining the sales market. The farmer's role may have stayed relatively the same as the decades before us, but the approach has drastically changed due to data analytics. The increased need for a sustainable and consistent food supply raises new questions. Questions for reflection include:  What percentage of land should be dedicated to farming versus communities?  What other data should be gathered to ensure a good food source for generations while not negatively impacting the environment?  Data analytics will continue to play a significant role in improving farming methods for future generations.

1.2.5 Variety of Data
Data is all around us, and it is coming at ever-increasing rates and in many different formats. For example, when mobile phones first became popular, they had only a few megabytes of data storage and were limited to the variety of data they could store. These early mobile phones, used primarily for phone calls, could keep text messages, a couple of MP3 music files, and a few low-resolution photos. Modern-day mobile phones can come with up to a terabyte (1000 gigabytes) of storage. They can store a growing variety of data types, including high-definition video files, photographs, audio files, documents, apps, books, calendars, and emails, to name a few.
1.3.5 Social Example: DrivenData
Competitions run by DrivenData encourage data professionals to find solutions to real-world problems. One such competition challenges entrants to predict the level of earthquake damage by aspects of building location and construction. This information can assist planners to determine, in advance, which buildings may withstand an earthquake, and which may need preventive measures. All of the prize-winning solutions are then made available as open source for anyone to learn from or build on.
Figure for Climate Change

1.3.6 Environmental Example - Climate Change
One of the most visible uses of data analytics is the ongoing observations and predictions related to climate change and its impacts on society.  These are made possible by collecting and analyzing data from many sources, including satellites, ocean temperature sensors, air quality sensors, crop yields, and weather data.  Observations uncovered by data professionals around the world are changing how we see our interactions with our environment, spurring actions to counteract the harmful effects that could result from a warming climate.  Without this intensive analytic effort, we would be unable to envision the changes and coordinate the efforts to mitigate the potential damage. Several interactive public dashboards show the impacts of our changing climate, including the IMF Climate Change Dashboard and the NOAA Global Climate Dashboard. Visit these dashboards to see the work done by the data professionals at these organizations to help the public visualize changes over time.

1.1.5 The Importance of Visualization
The data analysts at Data Crunchers work hard to create stories and reports from their clients’ data. Analysts rely heavily on visualization techniques to make the information relevant and actionable. Visualizations are a way to display data in a manner that is easily understood. The most common ways to represent data visually are charts and graphs.  There are many types of charts used to present information graphically. It is crucial to ensure that the type of visualization used best illustrates the pattern, problem, or trend that needs highlighting; not all types of visualizations are appropriate for all kinds of data.  Factors to consider when choosing a visualization: The number of variables, which are the characteristics measured, that need are shown The number of data points, or units of information, in each variable  Whether the data illustrates changes over time (hourly, daily, weekly)The need to make a comparison or correlation between different data points Often, analysts try a few different types of charts to choose the one that provides the most effective view of the information. 
Note
Note: To learn more about other types of charts, search the internet for Tableau Software’s guidelines for choosing the correct chart.

1.3.4 Social Examples
The United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) provides information management services to the humanitarian community by gathering and sharing data. By sharing the data and analysis, OCHA enables the coordination of resources, decision-making and funding. The Humanitarian Data Exchange (HDX), is a source that provides workers from the United Nations, (UN), non-governmental organizations (NGOs), government and universities with the tools to improve data sharing during times of crisis.      The availability of data enables organizations to better assist crisis-affected areas.  Predictive analytics can focus humanitarian efforts on preventive, rather than reactive, actions. There are organizations, such as DrivenData (https://www.drivendata.org/), which help humanitarian and social impact groups to find data-driven answers to difficult questions.

2.1.1 Defining Big Data
The data analysts at Data Crunchers introduced you to the concepts of analytics and the importance of visualizations. Now it is time to work alongside the company’s data engineers to learn about big data and the role that engineers play in building, maintaining, and ensuring that the organization’s data infrastructure is available and reliable. Big data is a term used to describe the massive volumes of digital data generated, collected, and processed. The term big data describes data that is either moving too quickly, is simply too large, or is too complex to be stored, processed, or analyzed with traditional data storage and analytics applications. Some examples of big data include data generated by postings to social media accounts, such as Facebook and Twitter, and the ratings given to products on e-commerce sites like Amazon marketplace. Size is only one of the characteristics that define big data. Other criteria include the speed of generated data and the variety of data collected and stored.

3.2.5 The Machine Learning Process
Developing a machine learning solution is seldom a linear process. Several trial-and-error steps are necessary to fine-tune the solution. The details of each step performed by the Data Crunchers data scientists as they work on the new weed identification and eradication model are as follows:Step 1. Data preparation - Perform data cleaning procedures such as transformation into a structured format and removing missing data and noisy/corrupted observations.   Step 2a. Learning data - Create a learning data set used to train the model. Step 2b. Testing data - Create a test dataset used to evaluate the model performance. Only perform this step in the case of supervised learning.   Step 3. Learning Process Loop - Selection. An algorithm is chosen based on the problem. Depending on the selected algorithm, additional pre-processing steps might be necessary.Step 4. Learning Process Loop - Evaluation. This selected algorithm's performance is evaluated on the learning data. If the algorithm and the model reach an acceptable performance on learning data, the solution validates the test data. Otherwise, repeat the learning process with a proposed new model and algorithm.Step 5. Model evaluation - Test the solution on the test data. The performances on learning data are not necessarily transferrable to test data. The more complex and fine-tuned the model is, the higher the chances are that the model will become prone to overfitting, which means it cannot perform accurately against unseen data. Overfitting can result in going back to the model learning process.   Step 6. Model implementation - After the model achieves satisfactory performance on test data, implement the model. Implementing the model means performing the necessary tasks to scale the machine learning solution to big data.

4.1.3 The Job Market
The uses for data, and especially Big Data, are multiplying rapidly. A report by FinancesOnline (2022) notes that 52% of businesses worldwide view data analytics and predictive analytics as primary components of their operations. The dependency on data usage is not surprising since the number of data businesses generate, store, sell, and share is more significant than ever. Consequently, the job market for data analytics professionals who interpret and transform this data is also growing. Source: Search the internet for the FinancesOnline report, 70 Relevant Analytics Statistics: 2021/2022 Market Share Analysis & Data.According to the World Economic Forum Future of Jobs Survey 2020, the top three jobs with the highest increased demand were Data Analysts and Scientists, AI and Machine Learning Specialists, and Big Data Specialists. 4.1.4 Tools and Skills
Because of the high projected job growth, there are many opportunities for entry-level positions in the data analytics field, some of which may not require previous experience. To prepare for this profession, become familiar with the job responsibilities and tools commonly used on the job. An excellent way to do this is by reviewing postings on job search platforms. If you are new to data analysis, you may start in an entry-level role as a junior analyst. Data analysts can often begin with no prior experience; however, they will need more on-the-job training to become familiar with company policies and procedures and to learn how to apply what they learned in school to a business setting.  Before you apply for that first job, it is a good idea to develop some of the core data analyst skills introduced in this course, including SQL, data management, statistical analysis, and data visualization. A few tools and skills commonly mentioned in job advertisements for entry-level positions include:  Demonstrated attention to detail  Solid verbal and written communication skills  Ability to work in a team  Proficiency with spreadsheets, such as Excel  Familiarity with SQL and databases Some experience with object-oriented programming (OOP) languages such as Python and Java Familiarity with visualization tools and presentations  As you gain experience, you will have opportunities to advance your career into other areas, such as data science, management, consulting, or different roles as a specialist in a specific field – healthcare, finance, or machine learning. Your career path as a data analytics professional will depend on your skills and interests. There is no one best approach when pursuing your career path. However, every data analytics career path begins with the fundamentals: Learning the essential tools, skills, processes, and of course, building a professional portfolio.

The three courses in the Cisco Data Essentials Pathway will help you start a strong portfolio and build your personal brand. Each course in the series is project-based, so as you proceed through the course, you will create work products that you can add to your portfolio. Document the process that you use to work through each project, including:  the question to answer or problem to solve  how you chose data that could inform your analysis  the methods you used to analyze the data  your observations and conclusions  reports and presentations that you created

4.3.2 Reflection
Planning a road trip takes time and thoughtful consideration. You must choose your final destination, set accommodations, map your route, and choose a reliable mode of transportation. Setting aside time to plan your trip will prepare you for a successful adventure.  Planning a road trip is similar to building a portfolio. You are embarking on a new career journey with the end goal of having a career in data science.  Start brainstorming what type of work interests you, what projects you might like to work on, and what branding and designing you want for your portfolio. This is an exciting time to start your career in data science. You have the opportunity to personalize your path and determine your future!

What is the role of a data analyst?
Data analysts query and process data, provide reports, summarize and visualize data. They leverage existing tools and methods to solve a problem. Data analysts need to understand basic statistical principles, cleaning different types of data, data visualization, and exploratory data analysis.

What is the role of a data scientist?
Data scientists apply statistics, machine learning, and analytic approaches to answer critical business questions.

Which three are skills that are typical for an entry level data analyst position? (Choose three.)
The skill sets that are commonly mentioned in job advertisements for entry-level positions with respect to big data are: 

Demonstrated attention to detail
Communication skills
Ability to work in a team
Proficiency with spreadsheets, such as Excel
Familiarity with SQL and databases
Familiarity with visualization tools and presentations

More on Starting Your Portfolio
A portfolio is a website that contains examples of your work at a basic level. Web sites are an excellent way to introduce yourself, provide contact information (including social media links), and relate to various projects you have completed or are currently developing. Data professionals use multiple methods to share their portfolios. Public repositories, such as GitHub, are where you can find many examples of ongoing projects, some complete with code samples and step-by-step processes used to create the work. In the next course, Data Analytics Essentials, you will learn how to organize your projects and share them with potential employers.
